# Microsoft Fabric Development Rules

> **Update Check**: At session start, check for skills-for-fabric updates by reading the remote `package.json` version from `https://github.com/microsoft/skills-for-fabric` (via `git fetch origin main --quiet && git show origin/main:package.json` or GitHub API with authentication) and comparing with the local `package.json` version. Show changelog if update available.

## Context
This project works with Microsoft Fabric for data engineering, warehousing, and analytics.
Primary API reference: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/fabric/articles/

## Development Guide
For authentication and deployment patterns, see **DEVELOPMENT-GUIDE.md** at repository root.

## Authentication
All operations require Azure AD tokens via `az login`:
```bash
az login
az account get-access-token --resource https://api.fabric.microsoft.com
```

## Developer Pattern: REST + Protocol
Developers use REST APIs to manage artifacts, then protocol-specific connections to access data:
- REST → ODBC for Warehouse
- REST → Spark for Lakehouse
- REST → XMLA/DAX for Semantic Models
- REST → KQL for Real-Time Intelligence

## Code Generation Rules

### Lakehouse & Spark
- Always use Delta Lake format for tables
- Use mssparkutils for Fabric-specific operations (fs, credentials, notebook)
- Include partition columns for large tables
- Run OPTIMIZE and VACUUM for table maintenance

### Warehouse (T-SQL)
- Check T-SQL surface area - not all SQL Server features are supported
- Use CTAS for large transformations
- Prefer stored procedures for reusable logic
- Always include TOP/LIMIT when exploring data

### Notebooks
- Tag first cell as "parameters" for parameterized notebooks
- Use mssparkutils.credentials.getSecret() for secrets
- Structure with clear markdown headers

### Pipelines
- Use expressions for dynamic content: @pipeline().parameters.Name
- Implement error handling with failure activities
- Add retry policies for transient failures

### KQL (Real-Time Intelligence)
- Always include time filters: where Timestamp > ago(1h)
- Use summarize for aggregations
- Prefer materialized views for frequent queries

### Semantic Models (DAX)
- Prefer measures over calculated columns
- Use DIVIDE() for safe division
- Document complex measures with comments

### Data Agents
- Use Python SDK within Fabric notebooks for rapid prototyping
- Provide custom instructions for domain-specific terminology
- Add few-shot examples to improve query accuracy
- Limit data sources to 5 maximum per agent

### Data Agent Evaluation
- Use pandas DataFrame with question/expected_answer columns
- Validate few-shot examples before adding to agents
- Test sandbox stage before production
- Track evaluation accuracy over time

## File Patterns

### PySpark Notebook
```python
# Parameters cell (tag as "parameters")
input_table = "default_table"

# Main logic
df = spark.read.format("delta").load(f"Tables/{input_table}")
```

### T-SQL
```sql
-- Always limit exploratory queries
SELECT TOP 100 * FROM dbo.TableName WHERE DateColumn >= '2024-01-01';
```

### KQL
```kql
TableName
| where Timestamp > ago(24h)
| summarize Count=count() by bin(Timestamp, 1h)
```
